                    1. Proper Nutrition for Dogs
                </p>
                <p class="mainText">
                    Ensuring that your dog receives a balanced and nutritious diet is crucial for their overall health. Dogs require specific nutrients such as protein, fats, carbohydrates, vitamins, and minerals in varying amounts depending on their age, size, and activity level. It’s important to feed your dog food that is appropriate for their life stage, whether they are a puppy, adult, or senior dog. High-quality commercial dog food often contains essential nutrients, but you should also be cautious of artificial additives or fillers. Always consult your veterinarian to determine the best diet for your dog, especially if they have any special dietary needs.
                </p>
            </div>
            <div class="mainColor2">
                <p class="secondaryTextTitle">
                    2. Regular Exercise and Mental Stimulation
                </p>
                <p class="mainText">
                    Physical exercise and mental stimulation are key to keeping your dog healthy, happy, and well-behaved. Regular walks, playtime, and interactive activities provide much-needed physical exercise, while puzzles, training sessions, and toys designed for mental stimulation help prevent boredom and destructive behavior. The amount of exercise needed depends on the breed, age, and health of the dog. High-energy dogs may require more intense exercise, while older or smaller dogs might do well with lighter activities. A balanced mix of both types of stimulation will keep your dog mentally sharp and physically fit.
                </p>
            </div>
            <div>
                <p class="secondaryTextTitle">
                    3. Grooming and Hygiene
                </p>
                <p class="mainText">
                    Routine grooming is essential to maintaining your dog's hygiene and overall health. Depending on your dog’s breed and coat type, they may require frequent brushing to prevent matting, regular baths to keep their skin clean, and nail trimming to prevent overgrowth. Grooming also provides an opportunity to check for signs of skin issues, parasites, or abnormalities that could indicate health problems. Oral hygiene is equally important, so regular brushing of your dog’s teeth helps prevent dental diseases. Maintaining proper grooming habits ensures that your dog feels comfortable and looks their best.
                </p>
            </div>
            <div class="mainColor1">
                <p class="secondaryTextTitle">
                    4. Health and Veterinary Care
                </p>
                <p class="mainText">
                    Regular veterinary visits are vital for monitoring your dog’s health and preventing potential issues. Routine check-ups, vaccinations, flea and tick prevention, and heartworm treatments are all important components of keeping your dog healthy. Additionally, regular screenings can help catch health problems early, such as kidney issues, joint problems, or heart conditions, which can be managed more effectively with early intervention. Being proactive about your dog’s health can extend their lifespan and improve their quality of life.
                </p>
            </div>
